Release notes

Sourced from micromatch's releases.

4.0.8

Ultimate release that fixes both CVE-2024-4067 and CVE-2024-4068. We consider the issues low-priority, so even if you see automated scanners saying otherwise, don't be scared.

Changelog

Sourced from micromatch's changelog.

[4.0.8] - 2024-08-22

  • backported CVE-2024-4067 fix (from v4.0.6) over to 4.x branch

[4.0.7] - 2024-05-22

  • this is basically v4.0.5, with some README updates
  • it is vulnerable to CVE-2024-4067
  • Updated braces to v3.0.3 to avoid CVE-2024-4068
  • does NOT break API compatibility

[4.0.6] - 2024-05-21

  • Added hasBraces to check if a pattern contains braces.
  • Fixes CVE-2024-4067
  • BREAKS API COMPATIBILITY
  • Should be labeled as a major release, but it's not.

I know I left a lot of comments but adding a new top-level bit of functionality to mlpack means we have to get everything right. :)  Most of my comments are pretty minor; hopefully they are helpful in cleaning things up and making them consistent across the codebase (one of my big focuses).

I do have some other general questions about the plan for this work:

 * Do you think it's a good idea to expose the template parameters for the `DecisionTreeRegressor` to users?  So that, e.g., they could change the splitting strategies in use for the individual weak learners, or other things along these lines.  In fact, I suppose it would be possible to simply templatize the weak learner itself---the restriction is just that it needs to be a regressor.  If we did this (and I would prefer if we did although it doesn't need to be this PR---but I do want to make sure it happens as it is nice functionality and helps us prove it when we say mlpack is flexible :smile:), we would also need to add a section to the Markdown documentation about the template parameter; but it should be pretty easy to do that using the existing other Markdown documentation files and just use the same format.

 * Are you planning on adding support for training on categorical features?  The `DecisionTreeRegressor` supports it, and it would be nice to add if possible.  This is another thing that we don't necessarily need to do as part of this PR but I would prefer if we tracked somehow that it still needs to be done (an issue is fine).

 * Are you planning on making a binding like `gradient_boosting_main.cpp`?  (Another thing that could be another issue if you prefer.  But fully fleshing out support for a new technique should probably involve this.)
 
Also, we should update `src/mlpack.hpp` to include `grad_boosting.hpp`. :+1:

Anyway this is really nice work, so don't let the large number of comments imply otherwise. 2. Improved parallelization of cluster assignments
3. Optimized batch clustering with better OpenMP usage
4. Introduced atomic operations to reduce critical sections
5. Enhanced memory locality for better cache utilization


I ran some benchmarks to compare the performance of the original implementation with the optimized version.

new task is only spawned every handful of levels.  That was the only way I saw speedup for dual-tree algorithms.  The idea of parallel dual-tree traversers (or even single-tree traversers) is a good idea, but probably needs a more in-depth dive that maybe we could do some other time.  Realistically, DBSCAN speedup would then come just from speeding up the range search itself as that (I think) is the majority of the runtime.

**Benchmark Results**
I ran a benchmark with the following settings:
```cpp
Number of data points: 100,000
Number of dimensions: 50
Number of clusters: 10
Maximum iterations: 100
```
**Here's what I found:**
```
Original version: 12.1609 seconds
OpenMP version: 6.98171 seconds
```

That's a 42.6% decrease in execution time!

The proposed governance model is described in 2 pull requests:

- https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas-governance/pull/17 describes the creation of a Steering Committee and the concept of Teams
- https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas-governance/pull/18 describes the responsibilities of the different Teams

According to the current governance model, 80% of the core team needs to vote on this issue, with at least 2/3 of the votes being in favor.  That means we need the votes of 17 individuals, with a positive vote of 14 members of the core team guaranteeing approval.

The rendered governance documents can be found at:
- Main Governance Document:  https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas-governance/blob/3b494821873a50fd1bdc8609445fa7d411848fe7/governance.md
- Description of Individual Teams:  https://github.com/pandas-dev/pandas-governance/blob/c0e5c586ed9b6dd95d180eff8a6e482571268fa9/teams.md

Voting will close on August 31, 2024.

Cast your vote in a comment below.
* +1: approve.
* 0: abstain.
* -1: disapprove

@pandas-dev/pandas-core

2) My concern about the [gestures vaguely] governance stuff is that it empowers people who are willing to spend their time in governance meetings and who are willing to wade through or write walls of text.

3) My preferred form of governance is an informal do-ocracy: the people who actually do the work make the decisions.  Both as a matter or principle and because they are more likely to actually understand what's going on.
